    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-08T09:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-08T09:54:00-05:00" n="872"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d872">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.24/5–845: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eddy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-08T18:00:00+03:06"
                            >May 8, 1945—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 9—1:46 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>197. ReDepts No. 125, April 27, 6 p.m., paragraph 4. British Minister told me
                    yesterday he has recommended British Government <pb facs="0905" n="893"
                        xml:id="pg_893"/> maintain parity in 1945 supply program by raising its
                    limit by an additional 375,000 pounds but he fears British Treasury will oppose.
                    I believe he is sincere in regretting influence of Jordan’s policy.</p>
                <p>He also told me Saudi Government has requested loan of 500,000 pounds sterling
                    from Gellatly-Hankey<note n="99" xml:id="d872fn99">Gellatly, Hankey amp; Co., a
                        British firm which served as banking agent for the Saudi Arabian
                        Government.</note> who are in a tight spot. Foreign Office refuses to mix in
                    the affair or to advise Gellatly-Hankey either way. Failing to receive to date
                    any assurance of total subsidy for 1945 or of cereals needed, Saudi Government
                    is seeking funds wherever it can and is not in good mood.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eddy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
